<p>In Part 1: On the cheap cheap, we‚Äôll cover how you can build a simple Jekyll based blog site, hosted for free on Github pages, without needing to know anything about coding or software development. All you‚Äôll need is a computer, a <a href="https://github.com/join?ref_cta=Sign+up&amp;ref_loc=header+logged+out&amp;ref_page=%2F&amp;source=header-home">Github account</a> and a little bit of knowledge about <a href="https://guides.github.com/features/mastering-markdown/">Markdown</a>.</p>

<h2 id="before-we-begin">Before we begin</h2>
<p>Before we delve too far into building the site, you first need to ask yourselves <em>‚ÄúWhat sort of blog site do I want?‚Äù</em>. Do you even want to build a blog? Perhaps you want a portfolio of your photography, an online CV with demos of your work, or maybe you just want a small single page site with a little bit of text. In the end, what you decide upon will determine how much work and time is required to get your site up and running, so it‚Äôs best to answer sooner rather than later.</p>

<p><strong>Don‚Äôt rush, take your time. Think about it over a cup of tea or coffee, I‚Äôll still be here when you‚Äôve decided</strong>.</p>

<p>If after much contemplation you have decided you only want/need a single page that‚Äôs awesome. This will be much quicker and easier for you. I‚Äôd recommend checking out Github‚Äôs very own <a href="https://guides.github.com/features/pages/">step-by-step guide</a>. It contains everything you need to know to get your site up and running using one of their curated single page jekyll themes. Follow this and you‚Äôll have your content hosted in no time.</p>

<p>For my Blog, Portfolio and CV peeps, <em>or those who don‚Äôt like the Github themes</em>, let‚Äôs keep going.</p>

<h2 id="choose-your-theme">Choose your theme!</h2>

<p>If you‚Äôre anything like me you feel that aesthetics are important, <em>perhaps overly so</em>. That is why I find the best way to start your blog site is to do a little theme shopping. If you want you can just Google <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=jekyll+themes">jekyll themes</a> but if you don‚Äôt want to browse through a bunch of random sites, here‚Äôs a few I searched earlier‚Ä¶</p>
<ul>
  <li><a href="http://jekyllthemes.org/">jekyllthemes.org/</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://jekyllthemes.io/free">jekyllthemes.io/free</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://jekyll-themes.com/free/">jekyll-themes.com/free/</a></li>
</ul>

<p>When you find your dream theme hold onto the page, you‚Äôll need it to navigate to the Github repository. Look for a button or link that mentions Github, Repository or Homepage, you should be taken to a page like this.</p>

